prefix: Approach the following question the way someone in high school would.
problem_prompt: Approach the following question the way someone in high school would. Compute $2011 \cdot 2012 \cdot 2013 \cdot 2014$ modulo 5.
solution: Using the properties of modular arithmetic, $2011 \cdot 2012 \cdot 2013 \cdot 2014 \equiv 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 4$ modulo 5. Continuing, $1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 4 \equiv 4$ modulo 5, so $2011 \cdot 2012 \cdot 2013 \cdot 2014 \equiv \boxed{4}$ modulo 5.
gpt_response:
To compute $2011 \cdot 2012 \cdot 2013 \cdot 2014$ modulo 5, we can first find the remainder when each number is divided by 5.

$2011 \equiv 1 \pmod{5}$  
$2012 \equiv 2 \pmod{5}$  
$2013 \equiv 3 \pmod{5}$  
$2014 \equiv 4 \pmod{5}$  

Now, we can multiply the remainders together and find the remainder when the product is divided by 5. 

$1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 4 \equiv 24 \equiv 4 \pmod{5}$

Therefore, $2011 \cdot 2012 \cdot 2013 \cdot 2014 \equiv 4 \pmod{5}$.
